eased functional residual capacity","Decreased residual volume","Decreased total lung capacity","Increased inspiratory reserve volume","Normal functional residual capacity with increased vital capacity"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECOPD is characterised by hyperinflation of the lungs with gas trapping and a loss of elastic recoil. This results in an \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased functional residual capacity\u003C/strong\u003E (FRC) and increased \u003Cstrong\u003Eresidual volume \u003C/strong\u003E- ie the volumes of air left in the lung at the end of normal tidal expiration. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etotal lung capacity\u003C/strong\u003E is typically increased due to hyperinflation, not decreased. The \u003Cstrong\u003Einspiratory reserve volume\u003C/strong\u003E is usually decreased in COPD due to hyperinflation and flattening of the diaphragm, impairing the volume that can be inspired above normal tidal volumes. Whilst the vital capacity might be increased, this is due to the addition of an increased FRC, making \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal functional residual capacity with increased vital capacity \u003C/strong\u003Einconsistent with the pathophysiology and expected findings in COPD.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease causes air trapping leading to increased functional residual capacity and residual volume","Total lung capacity is typically increased in chronic obstructive pulmonary disease due to hyperinflation"],"references":["Kim V, Criner GJ. Chronic bronchitis and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. Am J Respir Crit Care Med. 2013 Feb 1;187(3):228-37. doi: 10.1164/rccm.201210-1843CI. Epub 2012 Nov 29. PMID: 23204254; PMCID: PMC4951627","Agarwal AK, Raja A, Brown BD. Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease. 2023 Aug 7. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32644707"